@node AddBuffers "AddBuffers"

    Reserves RAM memory in 512-character blocks
    for use by the disk system.  Adding up to
    25 or 30 blocks will speed up disk access.

    Usage:  AddBuffers <drive>: <numberofblocks>

    A command used in a NewShell CLI which
    allows you to substitute a phrase for a
    frequently-used command.  See/edit the file
    s:Shell-Startup for your default aliases.


@endnode

@node Alias "Alias"

    Usage:  Alias <name> [LOCAL|GLOBAL] <string>
            Alias <name> REMOVE  ;removes alias
            Alias          ;lists aliases
            Alias <name>   ;list alias' <string>

    LOCAL (default)--affect only current shell
    GLOBAL--use alias in all shells

    Note:  The <string> MUST be at end

    See also:  Unalias

@endnode

@node Ask "Ask"

    Normally used in scripts (q.v.), Ask prints
    the prompt string in the CLI window, then
    waits for a Y (yes) or an N (no) response.
    A Return response is the same as an N.

    Usage:  Ask <prompt>

    See also:  If, Execute
    Used primarily to assign a logical device
    name to a directory or subdirectory.  Other
    uses include listing current assignments and
    removing assignments.


@endnode

@node Assign "Assign"

    Usage:  Assign [<name>: {<dir>}|[LIST]|[EXISTS]]|[DEFER|PATH] [ADD] [SUBTRACT]
            Assign [LIST]           ;shows current assignments
            Assign <name>: [LIST]   ;removes entry shows remainder of assignments
            Assign <name> EXISTS    ;looks for entry. If found, displays assignment,
                                    ;otherwise sets the condition flag to WARN (5).

        DEFER assigns <name>: only when referenced.
        This means <name>: is not assigned until
        used, which prevents commands like Info
        from requesting that you mount the
        ASSIGNed volume until you have used it.
        PATH assigns when referenced, momentarily.
        The assignment would not be active until
        you (or the system) used it, and would
        cease to be active when you finished
        using it.

@endnode

@node Avail "Avail"

    Gives info about your system RAM memory.
    Shows how much memory is used, how much is
    available for use by new applications, and
    the total memory for each category of CHIP,
    FAST, and TOTAL.

    Usage:  Avail [CHIP|FAST|TOTAL]

    See also:  Chip or Fast

@endnode

@node BindDrivers "BindDrivers"

    This command is usually found in the
    Startup-Sequence file.  It checks the
    Sys:Expansion directory for hardware drivers
    to provide support for add-on hardware.
    This allows the automatic configuration of
    add-on hardware.

    Usage:  BindDrivers

@endnode

@node Break "Break"

    Used to notify a process by setting its
    attention flags.  This generally causes the
    process to exit.  Equivalent to Ctrl-C
    through Ctrl-F typed in the process window.

    Usage:  Break <process> [ALL]|[[C] [D] [E] [F]]

@endnode

@node CD "CD"

    The Change Directory command.

    Usage:  CD         ;shows current directory
            CD <path>  ;changes directory
                       ;to new path
            CD :       ;change to root dir.
            CD /       ;change to parent dir.

@endnode

@node ChangeTaskPri "ChangeTaskPri"

    Allows you to change the priority (or
    importance) of the specified process (or the
    current CLI if no process specified).  The
    normal priority is 0.  Although the range is
    from -128 to 127, priorities greater than +5
    are not recommended.  See also:  Status

    Usage:  ChangeTaskPri <priority> [<process>]

@endnode

@node History "History"

    In a NewShell CLI, you can use the up- and
    down-arrow keys to display commands
    previously entered.  Press <Return> to
    select the displayed command, or edit the
    command with the left- and right-arrow keys.
    To quickly find a previous command, type one
    or more of the first letters of the command,
    then press Shift-up-arrow or Ctrl-R.

@endnode

@node Copy "Copy"

    Copies files and directories.  You can use a
    pair of doublequotes ("") to indicate the
    current directory as the destination.
    Pattern matching can be used for the source
    name (if just a directory is specified, all
    files in the directory are copied).  A
    destination directory will be created if it
    does not already exist.

    Usage:  Copy [FROM] <name> [TO] <name> [ALL]
                 [QUIET] [BUF|BUFFER=<nn>] [CLONE]
                 [DATE] [COM] [NOPRO]"

    ALL   - include any subdirectories and files
    QUIET - don't display names of files copied
    BUF=<nn>, BUFFER=<nn> - reserves <nn> 512-
    byte buffers for the copy (default = 200)
    CLONE - copy date, comment, protection bits
    DATE  - preserve the creation date
    COM   - copy any comment (see FileNote)
    NOPRO - don't copy the protection bits

@endnode

@node CPU "CPU"

    This program can enable the cache(s) of the
    68020/30/40 CPUs, as well as utilize any MMU
    (memory management unit) to place the system
    ROM (read-only memory) into higher-speed
    RAM.  It can also be used to detect which
    CPU (central processing unit) is used.

    Usage:  CPU [options] ;just "CPU"-show state

    Options:    [FastRom|NoFastRom]
                [Cache|NoCache] [Burst|NoBurst]
                [InstCache|NoInstCache]
                [InstBurst|NoInstBurst]
                [DataCache|NoDataCache]
                [DataBurst|NoDataBurst]
                [Check [68010,68020,68030,68881,68882,68851,MMU,FPU]]

@endnode

@node Date "Date"

    Shows the time and date.
    Can optionally set the time and date.

    Usage:  Date      ;shows time, date
            Date TOMORROW|YESTERDAY ;adjust date
            Date [dd-mmm-yy] [hh:mm]
                 [TO <filename>]|[VER <filename>]
                 TO or VER - send date to <filename>

@endnode

@node Delete "Delete"

    Deletes one or more files or directories.  Q
    or QUIET suppresses the display of the files
    being deleted.  ALL with a directory name
    deletes all files and subdirectories within
    the directory as well as the directory.

    Usage:  Delete {<name|pattern>} [Q|QUIET]
            Delete <directoryname>  [ALL] [Q|QUIET]

@endnode

@node Dir "Dir"

    Provides a listing of files and directories
    in a given directory or subdirectory.

    Usage:  Dir [OPT A|I|AI|D] [ALL]
                [DIRS] [INTER] [FILES]

    ALL    - include listings of subdirectories
             (same as OPT A)
    DIRS   - directories only (same as OPT D)
    FILES  - displays only files
    INTER  - interactive mode (same as OPT I)
    OPT AI - combines OPT A and OPT I

    Interactive mode displays a single file or
    directory at a time and prompts with a
    question mark.  Enter "E" to enter a
    directory, "B" to exit a directory or to
    stop (if at the top level), "DEL" to delete
    the file or empty directory, "T" to type
    the file (Ctrl-C stops the typing), or "C"
    to enter an AmigaDOS command on the next
    line for execution.

@endnode

@node DiskChange "DiskChange"

    Used mainly with drives that do not support
    automatic disk-change detection, DiskChange
    makes AmigaDOS consider the disk in the
    specified drive to be newly inserted.

    Usage:  DiskChange <drive>:

@endnode

@node DiskDoctor "DiskDoctor"

    Used in the event of a diskette failure,
    DiskDoctor attempts to repair the corrupt
    floppy enough to allow you to copy any good
    files to another device.  On FastFileSystem
    partitions, be sure the DOSType keyword in
    the MountList is set to 0x444F5301.

    Usage:  DiskDoctor <drive>:

@endnode

@node Echo "Echo"

    A command generally used in scripts (q.v.)
    to print a string in the CLI/Shell window.

    Usage:  Echo <string> [NOLINE] [FIRST <nn>] [LEN <nn>]

            NOLINE - suppresses the output of a new line
            FIRST <nn> - start with the <nn> character
            LEN <nn> - display <nn> characters

@endnode

@node Ed "Ed"

    Ed is a screen-oriented text editor.

    Usage:  Ed [FROM] <name> [SIZE <n>]

@endnode

@node Edit "Edit"

    Edit is a line-oriented editor which works
    on only one line at a time.

    Usage:  Edit [FROM] <name> [TO] <name>

@endnode

@node Else "Else"

    Used in scripts (q.v.) with If/EndIf.
    Commands following the Else command are
    executed when the IF conditional is not met.
    This command is not required for If/EndIf.

    Usage:  Else          ;between If and EndIf.

@endnode

@node EndCLI "EndCLI"

    Ends the current CLI/Shell and closes its
    window.  This internal command is a synonym
    for EndShell.

    Usage:  EndCLI

@endnode

@node EndIf "EndIf"

    Marks the end of a series of one or more
    AmigaDos commands following an IF (or an
    ELSE) script command, which are executed if
    the condition tested in the IF command
    evaluated to TRUE (or FALSE for ELSE).

    Usage:  EndIf

    See also: Scripts, If, Else

@endnode

@node EndShell "EndShell"

    Ends the current CLI/Shell and closes its
    window.  You can also use EndCLI as a
    synonym for this internal command.

    Usage:  EndShell

@endnode

@node EndSkip "EndSkip"

    Scripting command (q.v.).  Terminates a Skip
    block.  When EndSkip is encountered during a
    Skip, execution resumes on the line after
    the EndSkip, and the condition flag is set
    to WARN.

@endnode

@node Eval "Eval"

    Evaluates simple 1- or 2-argument integer
    expressions.  Decimal is the default; use 0X
    or #X before hexadecimal numbers and a
    leading 0 or # before octal numbers.

    Usage:  Eval <value1> <operation> [<value2>]
                  [TO <file>] [LFORMAT=<string>]

    Operations:
      +   (addition)         ~    (not)
      -   (subtraction)      <<   (left shift)
      *   (multiplication)   >>   (right shift)
      /   (division)         -    (negation)
    mod   (modulo)           xor  (exclusive or)
      &   (and)              eqv  (bitwise
      |   (or)                    (equivalence)

    LFORMAT string options:
      %X<n>  <n> digits of hexadecimal output
      %O<n>  <n> digits of octal output
      %N     decimal output
      %C     character output
      *N     output a new line

    Example:  Eval 0X9F / 12 LFORMAT="Ans=%X4*N"

@endnode

@node Execute "Execute"

    This command is used to "execute" script
    files which contain AmigaDOS commands.  When
    such a file is executed, each command in the
    file is executed as if typed in by hand.

    Usage:  Execute <scriptfile> [{<arguments>}]

    If the scriptfile's script bit is set (see
    Protect), "Execute" need not be specified.

@endnode

@node FailAt "FailAt"

    Used in a script file to set the error level
    at or above which the script will exit.  A
    program or scripting command will return
    this error code upon completion.  The
    default error level is 10.

    Usage:  FailAt <n>
            FailAt   ;returns current fail level

@endnode

@node Fault "Fault"

    Returns the corresponding error message for
    the fault code specified.

    Usage:  Fault [<n>]

@endnode

@node FileNote "FileNote"

    Attaches a file note to a file, which can
    be viewed with the List command.  The file
    note should not be more than 79 characters.
    Enclose your note in doublequotes if it has
    spaces.

    Usage:  FileNote [FILE] <file> COMMENT <comment>

@endnode

@node Get "Get"

    Used to obtain the string assigned to a
    variable associated with the current shell
    process.  Useful for scripts (q.v.) and
    ARexx-compatible applications.

    Usage:  Get <name>

    See also:  Set, Unset

@endnode

@node GetEnv "GetEnv"

    Returns the value of the specified environ-
    ment variable.

    Usage:  GetEnv <name>

    See also:  SetEnv, UnsetEnv, Get, Set

@endnode

@node IconX "IconX"

    Used to launch script files from Workbench.
    Just attach a project icon to your script
    file.  (IconEdit can be used to do this.)
    Then set the default tool of the icon via
    the Info menu item of Workbench to c:IconX.
    You can set WINDOW= and DELAY= tool types if
    you choose, then select SAVE.

    Usage:  IconX  ;not normally used this way

@endnode

@node IF "IF"

    Used in script files.  If the condition is
    true, the subsequent script commands are
    executed until an Else or an EndIf is
    encountered.  Supports environment variables
    by prefacing each with a $ character.
    To detect an unset (or null) parameter, use

    IF <a> EQ "".

    Usage:  If [NOT] [WARN] [ERROR] [FAIL]
              [<string> EQ|GT|GE <string>]
              [VAL] [EXISTS <file>]

    EQ - Equal to.  String case is disregarded.
    GT - Greater Than.  Use NOT GE for LT
    GE - Greater Than/Equal.  Use NOT GT for LE
    If previous return code >= 5, WARN is true;
    if >= 10, ERROR is true; if >=20, FAIL.

    See also:  Else, EndIf, Scripts

    Script example:

      IF EXISTS MyFile.doc
            COPY MyFile.doc RAM:Temp
      ELSE
            ECHO "File does not exist!"
      ENDIF

@endnode

@node Info "Info"

    Provides mounting, space and other status
    information on the volumes mounted or
    previously mounted.  Specify a volume for
    info on just that volume.

    Usage:  Info [<device>]

@endnode

@node Install "Install"

    Used to make a floppy disk bootable.

    Usage:  Install [DRIVE] <drive>: [NOBOOT]
                    [CHECK] [FFS]

    <drive> is DF0, DF1, DF2 or DF3

    NOBOOT makes a non-bootable AmigaDOS disk.
    CHECK verifies valid boot code installed.
    FFS specifies the Fast Filing System.

@endnode

@node IPrefs "IPrefs"

    This utility reads your preferences settings
    found in SYS:Prefs/Env-Archive and installs
    them.  It is usually found in your startup-
    sequence file.

    Usage:  IPrefs

@endnode

@node Join "Join"

    Used to concatenate (join together) 2 or
    more files.  The final name cannot be the
    same as one of the previous names.

    Usage:  Join {<name|pattern>} AS|TO <name>

@endnode

@node Lab "Lab"

    Defines a label in scripts (q.v.) which can
    be used as a destination for the Skip command.

    Usage:  Lab <name>

    See also:  Skip, EndSkip

@endnode

@node List "List"

    Gives more info about files and directories
    than Dir.  Used by SPAT and DPAT; examine
    them in your S: directory for examples.
    List does not sort the directory.  If no
    options are specified, List displays each
    filename, its size, its protection bit
    settings, its creation date and time, and
    any attached comment (see FileNote).

    Usage:  List [<dir|pattern>] [P|PAT <pattern>]
                 [KEYS] [DATES] [NODATES] [TO <name>]
                 [SUB <substring>] [SINCE <date>]
                 [UPTO <date>] [QUICK] [BLOCK] [NOHEAD]
                 [FILES] [DIRS] [LFORMAT=<string>]

    P or PAT - show files that match <pattern>
    KEYS - displays the block number of each
           file header or directory
    DATES - displays dates as DD-MMM-YY ;default
    NODATES - no date/time info displayed
    TO - output goes to specified file
    SUB - search for files containing <string>
    SINCE/UPTO - show files since/up to <date>
    QUICK - just the names of files and dirs
    BLOCK - file sizes in blocks, not bytes
    NOHEAD - suppress display of header
    FILES/DIRS - files only/directories only
    LFORMAT string options:  LFORMAT="<string>"

    %S used once:  filename only
           twice:  path, filename
          thrice:  path, filename, path
      four times:  path, filename, path, filename

@endnode

@node LoadWB "LoadWB"

    Loads Workbench.  Usually found in your
    Startup-Sequence.

    Usage:  LoadWB [DELAY]|[-DEBUG]

    DELAY causes LoadWB to wait 3 seconds before exiting.
   -DEBUG adds a special menu for debugging.

@endnode

@node Lock "Lock"

    Locks volumes to prevent writing to them.
    If optional 4-character password is used to
    lock, same password must be used to unlock.

    Usage:  Lock <drive> [ON|OFF] [<password>]
            Lock <drive>          ;removes lock

@endnode

@node MakeDir "MakeDir"

    Creates a new directory or subdirectory.

    Usage:  MakeDir <dir>

@endnode

@node MakeLink "MakeLink"

    Creates a file which "links" or points to
    another file, which can be on another volume
    if the keyword HARD is not specified.  When
    the first file is referenced by a command,
    the second file will be used.  If the file
    is on another volume, a requester may appear
    asking for the volume.  HARD links may only
    be made between files on the same volume.

    Usage:  MakeLink [FROM] <file> [TO] <file> [HARD|SOFT]

@endnode

@node Mount "Mount"

    Gets the <device> parameters from the
    Devs:MountList file or the <mountlist> file,
    then installs the device, usually a drive,
    according to those parameters.

    Usage:  Mount <device> [FROM <mountlist>]

@endnode

@node NewCLI "NewCLI"

    In AmigaDOS 2.0, this command is a synonym
    for NewShell (q.v. for more info).

    Usage:  NewCLI [CON:<x>/<y>/<w>/<h>/<title>
                   [/CLOSE]] [FROM <file>]

@endnode

@node NewShell "NewShell"

    Opens a new Shell CLI (command line
    interface) process, complete with window,
    alias support, command line editing and
    history.  Uses Sys:System/CLI.

    Usage:  NewShell [CON:x/y/w/h/title[/CLOSE]] [FROM <file>]

    x,y    window starting coordinates
    w,h    window width and height
    title  window title.  If spaces, put the
           entire CON: expression in quotes
    CLOSE  adds Close gadget to window
    FROM   takes commands from startup file

    See also:  Alias, History

@endnode

@node Path "Path"

    Indicates the current directories which will
    be searched, in order, for the commands you
    specify on the command line.  Also used to
    set the path to a directory or to add more
    directories to the current path.

    Usage:  Path [SHOW] [RESET] [QUIET]
                 [ADD {<directoryname>}]

    SHOW   shows current path--same as just PATH
    RESET  resets path to current dir and C: and
           directories that follow RESET
    QUIET  when SHOWing, avoids requesters for
           unmounted volumes

    See also:  CD, Prompt

@endnode

@node Prompt "Prompt"

    Changes the system prompt of the current
    Shell.  Use doublequotes if you want a space
    in the new prompt.  Prompt accepts ANSI
    escape sequences (use an asterisk for the
    escape character as shown below).

    %S - displays the current directory
    %N - displays the current process number

    Usage:  Prompt <promptstring>

    Example:  Prompt "*E[41;33m%N.%S>*E[40;31m"

    will display the process number and current
    directory in inverse video.

    Recommended:  Place your favorite Prompt
                  command in S:Shell-Startup.

@endnode

@node Protect "Protect"

    Changes the protection bits on the
    specified file.  The protection bit settings
    can be viewed with the List command.

    Usage:  Protect [FILE] <file|pattern>
                    [FLAGS] <[+|-]StatusBits> [ADD] [SUB]

    StatusBits:  r)ead, w)rite, e)xecutable, d)eletable, s)cript, p)ure, a)rchive

    FILE  indicates which file to protect
    FLAGS shows which StatusBits to set.  If you
          omit a StatusBit, it is not set.
    ADD   and SUB are synonyms for + and -. These
          allow you to modify specific StatusBits
          without affecting others"

@endnode

@node Quit "Quit"

    Terminates the execution of a script when
    encountered, with optional <return code>.

    Usage:  Quit [<return code>]

@endnode

@node Relabel "Relabel"

    Used to change the name of a volume.

    Usage:  Relabel [DRIVE] <drive>: [NAME] <name>

@endnode

@node RemRAD "RemRAD"

    Removes the recoverable RAM disk drive by
    first making it as small as possible, then
    eliminating it entirely upon reboot.  The
    FORCE option will remove it even if it is in
    use.

    Usage:  RemRAD [<drive>] [FORCE]

@endnode

@node Rename "Rename"

    Changes the name of a file or directory.
    Can also be used to move a file from one
    directory to another on the same volume.

    Usage:  Rename [FROM] <file> [TO|AS] <name>
            Rename <oldpathname> <newpathname>

@endnode

@node Resident "Resident"

    Installs an AmigaDOS command in RAM, so that
    it does not have to be loaded from disk each
    time it is needed.  The command must be
    "pure", that is, it must be re-executable
    and re-entrant.  See also:  Protect.

    Usage:  Resident <residentname> <file>
                    [REMOVE]|[ADD]|[REPLACE]
                    [PURE] [SYSTEM] [DEFER]

    Resident     ;list resident commands

    REMOVE/ADD  - remove from or add file to list
    REPLACE     - default; replace any existing cmd
    PURE        - load as pure (even though pure bit
                  not set; not recommended)
    SYSTEM      - add to or search the system portion
                  of the (non-removable) resident list.
    DEFER       - Don't ""resident"" until referenced.

@endnode

@node Run "Run"

    Used to launch commands in a multitasking
    manner.  After the command is "run", it will
    be executing as a separate task, and you can
    continue using the CLI or Shell from which
    the command was launched.  Use + at the end
    of each line to enter multiple commands.

    Usage:  Run <command> [{+ <command>}]
            Run <Nil: >Nil: <command>

@endnode

@node Search "Search"

    Looks through the specified files for a
    search string, or looks for a file.  For use
    with scripts, Search returns 0 if found, and
    5 (WARN) otherwise.  Abandon current file
    with Ctrl-D, or cancel with Ctrl-C.

    Usage:  Search [FROM] <name|pattern>
                   [SEARCH|NAME] <string|pattern> [ALL]
                   [NONUM] [QUIET] [QUICK] [FILE] [PATTERN]

    ALL     - include subdirectories in the search
    NONUM   - don't print line numbers
    QUIET   - no output; used with scripts
    QUICK   - more compact output
    FILE    - look for file rather than string
    PATTERN - allows pattern matching symbols in text string

@endnode

@node Set "Set"

    Used to assign a string to a variable
    associated with the current shell process.
    These variables can then be accessed by
    ARexx-compatible software or scripts.

    Usage:  Set <name>=<string>

    See also:  Get, Unset

@endnode

@node SetClock "SetClock"

    Used to set or read the system's hardware clock.

    Usage:  SetClock LOAD|SAVE|RESET

    LOAD  - sets system time from hardware clock
    SAVE  - sets hardware clock from system time
    RESET - completely resets the clock.

@endnode

@node SetDate "SetDate"

    Used to change the datestamp on a file.
    The datestamp can be viewed with the List command.

    Usage:  SetDate <file|pattern> [<date> <time>]
            SetDate <file>  ;sets to current

@endnode

@node SetEnv "SetEnv"

    Used to define an environment variable.
    Such variables are stored in ENV:  and are
    available to all processes.  If no <string>
    is included, the specified variable is
    deleted.

    Usage:  SetEnv <name> [<string>]

    See also:  GetEnv, UnsetEnv, Set, Get

@endnode

@node SetFont "SetFont"

    Used to set a new system font.

    Usage:  SetFont <fontname> <fontsize>
                    [SCALE] [PROP] [BOLD]
                    [ITALIC] [UNDERLINE]

    See also:  Font, FixFonts

@endnode

@node Skip "Skip"

    Used to bypass commands in a script file.
    Skips to <label>, or the next label if one
    is not specified (see Lab) or the line after
    the EndSkip (q.v.) command.  The BACK option
    starts the search for the label from the
    last Execute command, or the beginning of
    the file if it has no Execute commands.

    Usage:  Skip [<label>] [BACK]

@endnode

@node Sort "Sort"

    Sorts a small file alphabetically by line.

    Usage:  Sort [FROM] <name> [[TO] <name>]
                 [COLSTART <n>] [CASE] [NUMERIC]

    COLSTART - start sort on specified column
    CASE     - makes the sort case-sensitive

@endnode

@node Stack "Stack"

    Views or sets the stack size of the current
    CLI or Shell.

    Usage:  Stack      ;shows current stack size
            Stack <n>  ;sets n bytes of stack

@endnode

@node Status "Status"

    Shows info about a specific CLI/Shell
    process, or all processes if a number is not
    given.  If COMMAND is specified and the
    command is found, 0 is returned; otherwise,
    5 (WARN) is returned.

    Usage:  Status [<process>] [FULL] [TCB]
                   [CLI|ALL] [COMMAND=<command>]

    FULL    equivalent to TCB and CLI
    TCB     shows priority, stacksize, and global
            vector size of each process
    CLI     shows CLI processes and names of
            current CLI commands, if any
    COMMAND specifies a CLI command to look for

@endnode

@node Type "Type"

    Types a text file to the CLI or specified
    output stream.  It can also display a hexa-
    decimal listing, or a listing with line
    numbers.

    Usage:  Type <filename> [TO <name>] [OPT H]|[HEX]|[OPT N]|[NUMBER]

@endnode

@node Unalias "Unalias"

    Clears the current alias assignment. The
    original alias will no longer undergo
    substitution when entered in a Shell CLI.

    Usage:  Unalias <name>

    See also:  Alias

@endnode

@node Unset "Unset"

    Used to unassign (clear) a variable
    associated with the current shell process.

    Usage:  Unset <name>

    See also:  Get, Set

@endnode

@node UnsetEnv "UnsetEnv"

    Clears the specified environment variable.

    Usage:  UnsetEnv <name>

    See also:  GetEnv, SetEnv

@endnode

@node Version "Version"

    Shows the current version of Workbench (with
    no arguments), or the version and revision
    number of a library or device or the
    Workbench disk.  Can be used in scripts;
    returns 0 if version (and optional revision)
    is greater or equal to specified values, 5
    if not.

    Usage:  Version [<library name|device name>]
                    [<version #> [<revision #>]]|[<unit #>]

@endnode

@node Wait "Wait"

    Tells AmigaDOS to wait for a specified time,
    or until a particular time of day.  Default
    is 1 second.  Useful in scripts (q.v.).

    Usage:  Wait <n> [SEC|SECS]|[MIN|MINS]
            Wait UNTIL <hh:mm>

@endnode

@node Which "Which"

    Shows you from which directory the specified
    command will be loaded.  Searches the
    resident list, then the current directory,
    then the path.  RES searches only the
    resident list, NORES excludes it.

    Usage:  Which <name> [NORES] [RES]

    See also:  Path

@endnode


@node WILDCARDS "WildCards"

The AmigaDOS's Pattern Matching Wildcards...
--------------------------------------------

?
     Matches any single character.  For example, FI?E would match FILE,
     FINE and FIRE but not FIE.

#
     Matches the following expression 0 or more times.  For example,
     FRE#D would match FRE, FRED, FREDD, FREDDD, etc.  #? will match
     anything.

(a|b|c)
     Matches any one of the items seperated by '|'.  For example,
     (D#?G|C#?T) would match DOG, CAT, DIG, COT, etc.

~
     The tilde, the upper left key on most keyboards, negates the
     following expression.  It matches all strings that do not match
     the expression.  For example, F~(ROG)#? will match FROM but not
     FROG.  ~(J#?) will match anything not starting with the letter J.

[abc]
     A character class: matches only the characters in the class.  For
     example, a[bcd] will match ab, ac and ad but not ae.

[~abc]
     The tilde here indicates a negated character class: matches only
     the characters not in the class.  For example, a[~bc] will match
     ad and ae but not ab and ac.

[a-z]
     Character range (only within character classes).  For example,
     [a-z] represents all the lowercase letters from a to z.
     [a-cx-z]#? would match any name starting with the letters a,
     b, c, x, y or z.

%
     Matches the null string.  For example, CA(M|%)P will match CAMP
     and CAP.

'
     The apostrophe, found on most keyboards just to the left of the
     return key.  This character is used to declare the following
     character to be a literal character, instead of a possible
     wildcard symbol.  This permits you to use the characters #, ?, |,
     %, (, ), [, ], *, ~ and even an apostrophe as themselves.  For
     example, YEAR#?'% will match YEAR1989%, YEAR1990% but not YEAR1989
     or YEAR1990 as would normally be the case

    NOTE: The term "expression", above, means either a single character
    (ex: #?), or an alternation (ex: #(ab|cd|ef)), or a character class
    (ex: #[a-zA-Z]).

Pattern Matching Examples:
--------------------------

A?B
     Matches any three letter names beginning with A and ending with B,
     such as AcB, AzB and alb.

A#BC
     Matches any name beginning with A, ending with C and having any
     number of Bs in between, such as AC, ABC, ABBC, ABBBC and so on.

A#(BC)
     Matches any name beginning with A and followed by any number of BC
     combinations, such as ABC, ABCBC, ABCBCBC and so on.

A(B|C)D
     Matches ABD or ACD.

ABC#?
     Matches any name beginning with ABC, regardless of what follows,
     such as ABCD, ABCDEF.info or ABCXYZ.

#?XYZ
     Matches any names ending in XYZ, reguardless of what precedes it,
     such as ABCXYZ and ABCDEFXYZ.

[A-D]#?
     Matches any name beginning with A, B, C or D.

~(XYZ)
     Matches anything but XYZ.

~(#?XYZ)
     Matches anything not ending in XYZ.

A(B|D|%)#C
     Matches ABC, ADC, AC (% means the null string), ABCC, ADCC, ACCC
     and so on.

@endnode

@node Why "Why"

    When a command fails (you'll get an error
    number), use this command to find out why.

    Usage:  Why

@endnode

@node Clock "Clock"

    A computer clock/alarm that supports analog
    and digital display formats.  <x>,<y>
    determine placement of the clock; <width>
    and <height> are for the analog clock only.

    Usage:  Run Clock [DIGITAL]
                      [<x> <y> [<width> <height>]]
                      [24HOUR] [SECONDS] [DATE]

@endnode

@node Display "Display"

    Shows IFF lo-res, hi-res, medium-resolution
    and HAM (hold-and-modify) pictures, in non-
    interlaced and interlaced modes.  Click in
    the upper left corner to exit the program.

    Usage:  Display <filename>

@endnode

@node Exchange "Exchange"

    Controls the Commodities programs (q.v.).
    All currently open commodities will be
    displayed in the Exchange window, with
    information.  Show/Hide opens/hides the
    selected commodity's window.  Disable/
    Enable turns a commodity off/back on.  Kill
    terminates the commodity.  On the left of
    the Exchange window, Hide hides the
    Exchange window, Quit closes the program.

    Usage:  Run Exchange [CX_POPKEY=<key>]

    CX_POPKEY  defines pop-up keystroke to
               activate the program's window
        <key>  Key or key combination, like: shift alt f9

@endnode

@node More "More"

    A text file viewer. Can launch your
    favorite editor when the EDITOR variable is
    set to the complete path to the editor
    (e.g., C:ED), by pressing Shift-E.

    Usage:  More <filename>

    Type the letter "h" to get on-line help.

    See also:  SetEnv, GetEnv.

@endnode

@node Say "Say"

    This program will speak your text via the
    Amiga's speech synthesizer.

    Usage:  Say [-m|-f] [-r|-n] [-s<speed>]
                [-p<pitch>] [-x <filename>]|"text"

    -m:  male voice     -f: female voice
    -r:  robot voice    -n:  natural voice

    -s<n> where 40<=n<=400 sets the speed of the
          spoken text.
    -p<n> where 65<=n<=320 sets the pitch.
          Change this if you change voice above.
    -x <filename> will speak the specified file.

@endnode

@node BRU "BRU"

    CLI-driven hard disk backup utility.
    Supports extensive options like file
    compression and file comparison.  Requires
    40000 bytes of stack (see Stack) to run.
    Uses s:BRUTAB configuration file.

    Usage:  BRU [options] ;use -h for help

    See also:  HDBackup

@endnode

@node Calculator "Calculator"

    This is a computerized version of the four-
    function pocket calculator.  Use the mouse
    to point to the button you wish to choose,
    then press the left mouse button. Or use
    the keys on the keyboard.

    Usage:  Run >Nil: <Nil: Calculator

@endnode

@node CMD "CMD"

    Redirects printing output from the specified
    device (serial or parallel) to a specified
    file.  Normally, output goes to a printer.
    This command sends any output to a file
    instead.

    Usage:  CMD <SERIAL|PARALLEL> <filename> [OPT i|s|m|n]

    OPT i - ignore files that start with 4 nulls
    OPT s - skip any short initial write; in
            screen dumps, this is usually a reset.
    OPT m - multiple files; stop with Ctrl-C, or
            Break if started with Run.
    OPT n - NOTIFY; provides helpful messages.

@endnode

@node Colors "Colors"

    This program works similarly to the Palette
    Preferences program (q.v.).  However, the
    setting is only used during the current
    Workbench session.  Unique to this program
    is the ability to pop up on the frontmost
    screen, even if it is not Workbench.

    Usage:  Colors

@endnode

@node GraphicDump "GraphicDump"

    Sends an image of your frontmost screen to
    the printer after a ten-second delay.  The
    delay allows you to move the screen you wish
    to print to the front.

    Usage:  GraphicDump [TINY|SMALL|MEDIUM|LARGE|xdots:ydots]

    TINY's      image is ~1/4 the printer's width.
    SMALL's     image is ~1/2 the width.
    MEDIUM's    image is ~3/4 the width.
    LARGE's     image is full width and the default.
    xdots:ydots specifies the width/height in dots:  640:200.


@endnode

@node HDBackup "HDBackup"

    A hard disk backup utility.  This program
    serves as an Intuition front end (i.e., uses
    buttons and menus) for BRU (q.v.).  You
    can define and save a configuration file
    which specifies which files/directories you
    wish to back up.

    Usage:  HDBackup

@endnode

@node IconEdit "IconEdit"

    This icon editor is easy to use.  After
    starting the program, just click on and drag
    the desired icon over IconEdit's editing
    area, then release the left mouse button.
    You can also define new icons, including
    type:  Tool, Project, etc.

    Usage:  IconEdit

@endnode

@node InitPrinter "InitPrinter"

    Usually started from Workbench.  Sends a
    string of ASCII characters to set up the
    printer for use.  This string is predefined
    by your printer selection in Preferences.

    Usage:  InitPrinter

    See also:  Printer

@endnode

@node KeyShow "KeyShow"

    This utility displays the key definitions
    defined for your keyboard by the SetMap
    program (q.v.).  Click on the Shift, Ctrl,
    and Alt keys to display the corresponding
    Shift-, Ctrl-, and Alt-<key> definitions.

    Usage:  KeyShow

@endnode

@node Memacs "Memacs"

    A popular text editor, useful for light
    editing and program development. Consult
    your manual for more details.

    Usage:  Memacs <filename>

@endnode

@node PrintFiles "PrintFiles"

    This print utility allows you to send any
    text file you specify to the printer.  The
    "-f" option outputs a formfeed after the
    file."

    Usage:  PrintFiles {[-f] <filename>}

@endnode

@node AutoPoint "AutoPoint"

    When active, this utility enables the
    selection (activation) of a window as soon
    as the mouse pointer moves over it.

    Usage:  Run AutoPoint

    Or drag its icon to the WBStartup window to
    enable it upon booting.

    See also:  Exchange

@endnode

@node IHelp "IHelp"

    IHelp lets you use your keyboard to perform
    some mouse-activated functions like auto-
    sizing a window to its largest or smallest
    size, or bringing the rearmost application
    window to the front.  See also:  Exchange

    Usage:  Run IHelp [CYCLE=<key>] [MAKEBIG=<key>] [MAKESMALL=<key>]

        <key>  Key or key combination, like: shift alt f9

        CYCLE  Will bring the rearmost appli-
               cation window to the front"
      MAKEBIG  Will enlarge the active window to
               its maximum size"
    MAKESMALL  Will reduce the active window to
               its smallest size"

@endnode

@node Blanker "Blanker"

    Opens a window showing the current delay
    before it will blank the screen to protect
    the phosphors on your monitor, if there is
    no mouse or keyboard activity"

    Usage:  Run Blanker [SECONDS=<n>]
                        [CX_POPUP=YES|NO] [CX_POPKEY=<key>]
                        [CX_PRIORITY=<n>]

    Or drag its icon to the WBStartup window to
    enable it upon booting.

    See also:  Exchange

@endnode

@node NoCapsLock "NoCapsLock"

    This Commodities program disables the
    CapsLock key when run.  No pop-up window;
    use the Exchange program (q.v.) to kill it.

    Usage:  Run NoCapsLock

    Or drag its icon to the WBStartup window to
    enable it upon booting.

@endnode

@node FKey "FKey"

    Allows you to define the regular and shifted
    function keys.  This overrides any other use
    of these keys.

    Usage:  Run FKey [{[S]F<n>=<string>}]

    Or drag its icon to the WBStartup window to
    enable it upon booting.

    See also:  Exchange

@endnode

@node AddMonitor "AddMonitor"

    This program is executed by your startup-
    sequence to enable the use of a A2024,
    MultiScan, or NTSC/PAL (for PAL/NTSC
    systems) monitor, when the corresponding
    file has been copied from the MonitorStore
    directory to a Monitors directory.

    Usage:  AddMonitor NUM=<Monitor#> NAME=<MonitorName>

    This program is automatically loaded by
    Workbench if the Mode_Names.info file is
    present in the WBStartup directory. Use the
    Information... Workbench menu item to see
    the names BindMonitor assigns to different
    pixel configurations.

@endnode

@node CLI "CLI"

    This program, when launched from Workbench,
    opens up a CLI (command line interface)
    shell window.  The usual method of opening
    up a new CLI shell from an existing Shell
    is via NewCLI or NewShell (q.v.), which use
    this program.

    Usage:  CLI

@endnode

@node DiskCopy "DiskCopy"

    Copies from the FROM disk drive to the TO
    disk drive, formatting the TO diskette as it
    copies.  First prompts for diskettes.  The
    source and destination drives can be the
    same for single-drive copies.

    Usage:  DiskCopy [FROM] <disk> TO <disk> [NAME <name>]

@endnode

@node FastMemFirst "FastMemFirst"

    Tells the Amiga to use Fast memory (q.v.)
    first, before the memory at $C00000.  This
    memory becomes chip memory when the Enhanced
    Chip Set (ECS) is installed.

    Usage:  FastMemFirst

    The Amiga has two kinds of random access
    memory, Chip and Fast.  The Amiga's computer
    chip can use either one for instructions
    and data.  But the Amiga's coprocessor chips
    (for video and sound support) can only talk
    to the Chip memory.

@endnode

@node FixFonts "FixFonts"

    Updates the .font files in your Fonts:
    directory after you have added or deleted
    fonts.

    Usage:  FixFonts

    See also:  Font, SetFont

@endnode

@node Format "Format"

    Used to initialize diskettes to prepare them for use.

    Usage:  Format DRIVE <drive> NAME <name>
                   [NOICONS] [QUICK] [FFS|NOFFS]

    NOICONS keeps that trashcan off your disk.
    QUICK   is used for previously formatted
            diskettes to just initialize the root block,
            the boot block, and the bitmap blocks.
    FFS     specifies Fast File System.
    NOFFS   specifies the default file system.

@endnode

@node NoFastMem "NoFastMem"

    Tells the Amiga to pretend that there is no
    Fast memory (q.v.) to provide compatibility
    with some older programs.  Works as a toggle
    when running under Workbench.  Use Ctrl-C to
    turn it off from the CLI, or Break if the
    program was started with Run.

    Usage:  Run <Nil: >Nil: NoFastMem

@endnode

@node RexxMast "RexxMast"

    This program is usually run by the execution
    of your startup-sequence.  It is the master
    ARexx control interface, allowing you to run
    ARexx script files and supporting other
    inter-process communications.

    Usage:  RexxMast

@endnode

@node SetMap "SetMap"

    Changes the key map (the default key defini-
    tions) for the keyboard.  The keymaps are in
    Sys:devs/keymaps.  Additional keymaps (for"
    Dvorak or other country keyboards) can be
    copied to this directory from the Extras
    disk's devs/keymaps directory.

    See: KeyShow

    Usage:  SetMap <keymapname>

@endnode

@node Font "Font"

    A Preferences program providing a means of
    selecting which fonts are used for Workbench
    icon text, screen text (menus, window and
    screen title bars, requesters) and screen
    default text (Shell window text, View By
    text, etc.).

    See also:  SetFont

@endnode

@node IControl "IControl"

    Workbench has several keystroke combinations
    for moving the Workbench screen to the front
    or moving the front screen to the back, or
    replying to a requester, etc.  The Prefs
    program IControl provides you with a means
    of changing the default keystrokes.  Other
    graphic interface controls can be enabled or
    changed here.

@endnode

@node Input "Input"

    The Input Preferences program controls mouse
    speed, acceleration, and double-click settings,
    as well as key repeat delay and speed.

    The Mouse Speed slider can be set to 1, 2,
    or 4 to determine how quickly your pointer
    moves across the screen when you move your
    mouse.  1 is fastest, while 4 may require
    that you pick up and move the mouse several
    times to get the pointer across the screen.
    Choose the Acceleration button if you wish
    your pointer to move a greater distance when
    you move the mouse more quickly.  You may
    want a slower mouse speed setting with
    acceleration.
    Next is the mouse double-click proportional
    gadget.  Drag the slider left for a shorter
    time allowed between two successive clicks
    of the left mouse button, or drag it right
    for a longer time to consider two clicks as
    a double-click instead of two single clicks.
    The Show button will highlight the square
    for your selected time, or double-click on
    the Test button for Yes/No timing feedback.

    The Key Repeat Delay determines how long
    after you press a key before it starts to
    repeat.  The Speed determines how fast the
    key repeats.  Press a key on the keyboard to
    view the effects of your choices in the test
    field gadget.

@endnode

@node Overscan "Overscan"

    This Preferences program allows you to
    define the actual screen area used for text
    and graphics.  You can also adjust the
    position of this image area on your monitor.

@endnode

@node Palette "Palette"

    This Preferences program allows you to set
    the Workbench default colors.  There are
    from 2 to 16 pens used by Workbench 2.0
    for icons, text and gadgets.  The leftmost
    color on the Preferences color bar is the
    background color.  Next is the main drawing
    pen color, used primarily for text.  The
    remaining colors are used for gadget
    highlights as well as contrast and variety.

    Click on a color box to select it, then
    click and drag the sliding gadgets
    in the red (R), green (G), or blue (B)
    proportional gadgets to set the color in
    that color box.  Choose Reset Colors to
    return to your original color setting.

@endnode

@node Pointer "Pointer"

    The Pointer Editor in Preferences allows you
    to define the shape and choose the colors of
    your sprite pointer.  The "Set Point" gadget
    allows you to indicate where the "hot spot"
    of your pointer is located.  Use the editor
    as you would a paint program. The Test
    button allows you to test your pointer.

@endnode

@node Printer "Printer"

    The Printer program of Preferences provides
    you with an easy means of selecting a
    printer software "driver" that matches your
    printer.  You can also use this section to
    tell the Amiga how to control your printer.
    Be sure to specify whether you are using a
    serial or a parallel printer.

    See also:  PrinterGfx

@endnode

@node PrinterGfx "PrinterGfx"

    Use this Preferences program to define the
    type of graphics output you desire from your
    printer.  Not all graphics modes are
    supported by all printers, so consult the
    printer appendix in your manual.
    COLOR CORRECT - tries to better match the
    screen colors to the printer colors.  Test
    by printing an image with solid red, green,
    and blue colors, first without any color
    correction, then with R, G, and/or B on.
    SMOOTHING - tries to remove the "jaggies"
    from diagonal lines."
    DITHERING - prints dots of different colors
    close together to "fool" the eye into seeing
    more colors or shades than actually exist.
    Ordered dithering uses patterns of dots.
    Halftone varies the dot thickness.  Floyd-
    Steinberg uses an error distribution method.
    SCALING - maps the image into the available
    resolution of the printer.  Normal scaling
    is Fraction.  Integer scaling guarantees
    that every image dot will produce one or
    more printer dots (affects aspect ratio).
    IMAGE - is either positive (as the image
    appears) or negative (reversed).  Affects
    only Black & White and Gray Scale.
    ASPECT - Horizontal is normal, Vertical
    rotates the image to appear "sideways".
    SHADE - determines whether your image will
    be printed in color, shades of gray, or in
    black and white.  Gray Scale 2 supports four
    shades of gray (for the A2024 monitor).
    THRESHOLD - says which colors will be white
    and which black for Black & White printing.
    DENSITY - is the resolution of the printed
    image.  The higher the density, the more dots
    will be used to create the picture.
    LIMITS - sets the width and height of the
    picture.  "Ignore" ignores these limits.
    "Bounded" uses the limits as the maximum
    picture size.  "Absolute" makes these limits
    the only size allowed.  Set either width or
    height to zero to maintain the aspect ratio,
    or set both to zero to use full printer
    width.  "Pixels" means the limits are in
    pixels, not inches.  "Multiply" says the
    width and height are factors to be
    multiplied by the actual picture size.

@endnode

@node ScreenMode "ScreenMode"

    Preferences ScreenMode program can be used
    to set the resolution used by Workbench.
    The interlaced mode displays twice as many
    scan lines as the normal mode.  Although
    this results in a higher resolution (finer)
    picture, some "flicker" may result without a
    special monitor and display adapter.

    You can also set Workbench's virtual size,
    number of colors, and scroll mode.
    Autoscroll means scroll the screen when the
    pointer gets to the edge of a visible screen
    that is smaller than the virtual screen.

@endnode

@node Serial "Serial"

    The Serial program of Preferences enables
    you to configure your serial port for use
    with a printer or modem.  Consult the manual
    that came with your printer or modem to
    determine the proper settings for baud rate,
    handshaking, parity, number of bits per
    character, and number of stop bits.

@endnode

@node Time "Time"

    This Preferences program allows you to set
    the date and/or time for the hardware clock
    and the system software clock (via "Save"),
    or just the software clock ("Use").  Click
    on the displayed month to cycle through the
    months.  Click on the desired day, then
    click on and drag the hour and minute
    sliders to the current time.

    See also: Date

@endnode

@node WBConfig "WBConfig"

    Use this Preferences program to make your
    Workbench window a backdrop window (or
    restore it to normal).  You can also enable
    the ability to move any Workbench window to
    the front by double-clicking on any exposed
    portion of the window.

    See also:  Autopoint

@endnode

@node WBpattern "WBpattern"

    This Preferences program can put different
    background patterns on your Workbench screen
    and/or Workbench windows "behind" your
    icons.  The "Text & Field" setting of the
    Font program may need to be selected so that
    icon text will be legible against some
    backgrounds.

@endnode

@node Information "Information"

    Usage syntax:  Don't type the brackets!

       <> encloses information (a parameter)
             required by the program.*
       [] encloses optional parameters.*
       {} indicates one or more entries.*
       |  separates choices, like ON|OFF.
       ;  indicates a following comment.

    * -- Don't type the brackets or braces!

    Notes:
    Internal commands are built-in to AmigaDOS
    and don't need to be loaded from disk.

    Many Preferences programs can be run from a Shell.

    The syntax:  PrefsProgram <prefsfile> ACTION USE

    Example:     Sys:Prefs/Printer Laser ACTION USE

@endnode

